      <h2>What We'd Do Differently</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Start with school-level sales.</strong> The product's value is clearest at scale — cross-classroom narrative worlds, longitudinal student data, admin dashboards.</li>
        <li><strong>Better free tier.</strong> Include the narrative engine for one classroom. Let teachers experience the full product. Limit scale, not features.</li>
        <li><strong>Template library.</strong> Ship with 50+ pre-built quest templates mapped to common curriculum standards. Reduce setup from hours to minutes.</li>
        <li><strong>AI-assisted content generation.</strong> Generate drafts, teacher reviews and edits, system learns preferences. Dramatically better quality with lower teacher workload.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why Include a Failure?</h2>
      <p>
        Aetheria didn't hit its targets. I'm including it anyway because the Google creative team explicitly values process documentation and honest reflection. The I→II→III pipeline worked as governance — it caught problems, preserved decisions, and enabled a clear post-mortem. The product needs iteration, but the system that produced it is sound.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's what governance as creative infrastructure looks like in practice: not preventing failure, but making failure legible and recoverable.
      </p>

